    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-6 leading-relaxed">One of the first questions people ask when starting to learn English online is: how much will it cost? The answer depends on many factors, including which platform you choose, the experience level of your tutor, and how often you want to take lessons. This guide breaks down everything you need to know about online English tutor prices in 2026.</p>

    <AdUnit slot="in-article" />

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">What affects the cost of online English lessons?</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Before looking at specific prices, it helps to understand what makes tutor costs go up or down. Several factors determine how much you will pay for a lesson.</p>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Tutor experience and qualifications.</strong> Native English speakers with teaching certifications like TEFL or CELTA typically charge more than non-certified tutors. A tutor with five years of experience will usually cost more than someone just starting out.</p>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Lesson length.</strong> Most platforms offer 30-minute and 60-minute lessons. Longer sessions usually give you a small discount per minute, but shorter lessons can be easier to fit into a busy schedule.</p>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Platform fees.</strong> Every tutoring platform adds its own service fee on top of what tutors charge. Some platforms take 15 percent of the tutor's rate, while others charge flat subscription fees. These fees affect the final price you pay.</p>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Package deals.</strong> Buying lessons in bulk often reduces the cost per session. Many platforms offer discounts when you purchase 10, 20, or more lessons at once.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Average prices by platform type</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Online English tutoring platforms generally fall into three categories, each with its own pricing structure.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Marketplace platforms</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Marketplace platforms like iTalki, Preply, and See Guru host thousands of tutors. Prices vary widely based on tutor experience. Here is what you can expect:</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-400 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Budget tutors:</strong> $5 to $15 per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Mid-range tutors:</strong> $15 to $30 per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Premium tutors:</strong> $30 to $60 per hour</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">See Guru is one of the most affordable options in this category. New tutors on See Guru often start at $10 per session, making it a great choice for beginners who want professional lessons without spending a lot of money.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Subscription platforms</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Platforms like Cambly and Verbling work on subscription models. You pay a monthly fee for access to unlimited or set numbers of lessons.</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-400 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Cambly:</strong> $99 to $199 per month</li>
      <li><strong>Verbling:</strong> $40 to $100+ per month depending on plan</li>
      <li><strong>Preply (subscription):</strong> $89 to $199 per month</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Subscription platforms work well if you plan to take multiple lessons per week. The monthly cost can be higher than pay-as-you-go options, but you often get better value per lesson when you use the service frequently.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Professional language schools</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Some learners prefer structured programs from established language schools. These tend to be the most expensive option.</p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-400 mb-6">
      <li><strong>EF Education First:</strong> $1,000 to $3,000 for courses</li>
      <li><strong>British Council:</strong> $20 to $50 per lesson</li>
      <li><strong>Wall Street English:</strong> $2,000 to $5,000 for programs</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">These programs often include additional materials, progress tracking, and certificates. However, the high prices make them less popular for casual learners or those on tight budgets.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Breaking down the real costs: what you get for your money</h2>
